answer:
Multiplying the numerator and denominator by the conjugate of the denominator, we have \begin{align*}
\dfrac{3+4i}{1+2i} \cdot \frac{1-2i}{1-2i} &= \frac{3(1) + 3(-2i) + 4i(1) + 4i(-2i)}{1(1) + 1(-2i) + 2i(1) -2i(2i)} \\
&= \dfrac{11-2i}{5} = \boxed{\dfrac{11}{5} - \dfrac{2}{5}i}.
\end{align*}

Using the quadratic formula, we find that the roots of the quadratic are $\frac{-5\pm\sqrt{5^2-4(3)(k)}}{6}=\frac{-5\pm\sqrt{25-12k}}{6}$. Since the problem tells us that these roots must equal $\frac{-5\pm i\sqrt{11}}{6}$, we have \begin{align*} \sqrt{25-12k}&=i\sqrt{11}
\\\Rightarrow\qquad \sqrt{25-12k}&=\sqrt{-11}
\\\Rightarrow\qquad 25-12k&=-11
\\\Rightarrow\qquad 12k&=36
\\\Rightarrow\qquad k&=\boxed{3}.
\end{align*}

